exas-style" accountability—the notion that decisions governing retention, promotion, and graduation should be based on a single test score—fails Latina/o youth and their communities. The contributors, many of them from Texas, scrutinize state policies concerning high-stakes testing and provide new data that demonstrate how Texas' current system of testing results in a plethora of new inequalities. They argue that Texas policies exacerbate historic inequities, fail to accommodate the needs and abilities of English language learners, and that the dramatic educational improvement attributed to Texas' system of accountability is itself questionable. The book proposes a more valid and democratic approach to assessment and accountability that would combine standardized examinations with multiple sources of information about a student's academic performance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aEducation : Multicultural Education. 4aEducation : Social Context of Education. 7aEDUCATION / Philosophy, Theory & Social Aspects.2bisacsh1 aAlamillo, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Ellen Riojas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Velasco, Jorge Ruiz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlores, Belinda Bustos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGARCÍA, Eugene E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHampton, Elaine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcneil, Linda Mcspadden, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPadilla, Raymond V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPalmer, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSloan, Kri